01:05:00.710 --> 01:05:03.950
to stay on the
contra-parallelograms track.

01:05:03.950 --> 01:05:06.050
But how do you force that?

01:05:06.050 --> 01:05:09.120
He didn't force it,
and so technically he

01:05:09.120 --> 01:05:10.550
did not solve this problem.

01:05:10.550 --> 01:05:13.492
He solved, that
solved this problem,

01:05:13.492 --> 01:05:14.950
which is that you
would get exactly

01:05:14.950 --> 01:05:16.750
the trajectory of a vertex.

01:05:16.750 --> 01:05:20.050
He solved the slightly weaker
problem, which is his point

01:05:20.050 --> 01:05:22.930
can travel along that curve.

01:05:22.930 --> 01:05:25.660
It can also travel
on other curves.

01:05:25.660 --> 01:05:27.160
But it's going to
be one dimensional

01:05:27.160 --> 01:05:28.380
because it is constrained.

01:05:28.380 --> 01:05:30.630
But there are these other
tracks you might conceivably

01:05:30.630 --> 01:05:31.940
be able to go on.

01:05:31.940 --> 01:05:33.679
In particular, you
can follow this track.

01:05:33.679 --> 01:05:34.845
There might be other things.

01:05:34.845 --> 01:05:37.050
And we'd like to
get rid of that.

01:05:37.050 --> 01:05:39.750
It turns out you can get
rid of that pretty easily.

01:05:43.290 --> 01:05:46.340
This problem was first noticed
by Kapovitch and Millson

01:05:46.340 --> 01:05:52.650
in like 2002 I think.

01:05:52.650 --> 01:05:53.970
Yeah.

01:05:53.970 --> 01:05:55.720
Well that's when it
finally got published.

01:05:55.720 --> 01:05:58.440
I think it was around for
a few years before that.

01:05:58.440 --> 01:06:02.730
And they observed that
for parallelograms you

01:06:02.730 --> 01:06:06.050
can fix it pretty easily
like in this picture.

01:06:06.050 --> 01:06:09.230
You have the
parallelogram a-b-c-d.

01:06:09.230 --> 01:06:12.040
You construct the
midpoints of a and b

01:06:12.040 --> 01:06:13.940
and the midpoints of d and c.

01:06:13.940 --> 01:06:15.910
How do you actually do this?

01:06:15.910 --> 01:06:19.490
I want that point x to stay
on the middle of that bar.

01:06:19.490 --> 01:06:21.020
You can do that
by making, if you

01:06:21.020 --> 01:06:23.360
want to construct a point
in the middle of a bar,

01:06:23.360 --> 01:06:25.630
you just add a tiny
triangle, where

01:06:25.630 --> 01:06:30.380
it's forced to be that
way, where a b equals,

01:06:30.380 --> 01:06:34.190
I mean the sum of a
and b equals a plus b.

01:06:34.190 --> 01:06:37.977
And if you want,
do we need this?

01:06:37.977 --> 01:06:40.060
I think you could just
construct those three bars.

01:06:40.060 --> 01:06:42.300
This makes a little
bit more rigid,

01:06:42.300 --> 01:06:47.050
but I don't think we
actually need that here.

01:06:47.050 --> 01:06:49.500
So you can force a vertex
to be along the midpoint

01:06:49.500 --> 01:06:54.120
there by making a tiny
triangle, a zero area triangle.

01:06:54.120 --> 01:06:58.480
And when you do that, I don;t
actually have a picture of it,

01:06:58.480 --> 01:07:02.070
we can look at the
countra-parallelogram I guess,

01:07:02.070 --> 01:07:05.052
it forces the thing to work.

01:07:05.052 --> 01:07:07.010
So for example, suppose
we go from the midpoint

01:07:07.010 --> 01:07:09.420
here to the midpoint there.

01:07:09.420 --> 01:07:12.690
That's going to stay parallel to
this segment and this segment.

01:07:12.690 --> 01:07:15.040
It's like two parallelograms
joined together.

01:07:15.040 --> 01:07:18.060
Okay, and if you went
here, and then you

01:07:18.060 --> 01:07:22.889
tried to go off into the
contra-parallelogram state,

01:07:22.889 --> 01:07:23.680
what would that do?

01:07:23.680 --> 01:07:26.780
Well you'd have like from
the midpoint of this segment

01:07:26.780 --> 01:07:29.350
to the midpoint of this segment.

01:07:29.350 --> 01:07:30.320
Holy cow.

01:07:30.320 --> 01:07:32.480
It's like they're right
on top of each other.

01:07:32.480 --> 01:07:34.355
So that's not going to
have the right length.

01:07:34.355 --> 01:07:37.210
Right now it's supposed to be
this length, same as the length

01:07:37.210 --> 01:07:39.040
a x.

01:07:39.040 --> 01:07:41.780
So if you try to jump
tracks you can't.

01:07:41.780 --> 01:07:44.560
It's really easy to force
to stay on the parallelogram

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:45.060
track.

01:07:48.120 --> 01:07:50.260
And then six years
ago in this class

01:07:50.260 --> 01:07:52.070
I posed, hey can we
do the same thing

01:07:52.070 --> 01:07:53.642
for the contra-parallelogram.

01:07:53.642 --> 01:07:55.850
Kapovich and Millson gave
some other very complicated

01:07:55.850 --> 01:07:56.980
solution.

01:07:56.980 --> 01:08:00.340
Turns out there's also
pretty easy way to fix

01:08:00.340 --> 01:08:05.320
the contra-parallelogram, which
is you add this pinpoint set up

01:08:05.320 --> 01:08:07.680
to be--- So these midpoints
will all be aligned

01:08:07.680 --> 01:08:09.950
because it's a
contra-parallelogram.

01:08:09.950 --> 01:08:11.900
You take the middle
and you bisect,

01:08:11.900 --> 01:08:16.060
you put x far away, it would
be very far down there.

01:08:16.060 --> 01:08:19.540
And you just make these
lengths be what they should be.

01:08:19.540 --> 01:08:21.399
And it's not so
obvious but you can

01:08:21.399 --> 01:08:24.160
prove that as the
contra-parallelogram moves,

01:08:24.160 --> 01:08:27.398
these edges will all
have the same length.

01:08:27.398 --> 01:08:29.770
It works.

01:08:29.770 --> 01:08:35.700
Whereas if you try to go
into the parallelogram state,

01:08:35.700 --> 01:08:37.240
and you measure
these links, they're

01:08:37.240 --> 01:08:38.439
going to be really tiny.

01:08:38.439 --> 01:08:40.300
Here they're really large.

01:08:40.300 --> 01:08:41.960
Am I doing that right?

01:08:41.960 --> 01:08:43.050
What am I measuring?

01:08:43.050 --> 01:08:45.500
No, the point is it's
not about those links.

01:08:45.500 --> 01:08:48.979
These guys have to be co-linear
in the contra-parallelogram

01:08:48.979 --> 01:08:51.800
case, but they are not collinear
in the parallelogram case,

01:08:51.800 --> 01:08:54.640
and this is essentially
forcing that co-linearity.

01:08:54.640 --> 01:08:57.140
So I don't want to go into the
details of how that's proved,

01:08:57.140 --> 01:08:58.630
it's in the textbook.

01:08:58.630 --> 01:09:02.060
But this bracing will force it
to say contra-parallelogram,

01:09:02.060 --> 01:09:04.580
that bracing will force
it to be a parallelogram,

01:09:04.580 --> 01:09:06.529
and then we actually
have proofed

01:09:06.529 --> 01:09:09.030
Kempe's universality theorem,
with just a slight tweak

01:09:09.030 --> 01:09:09.920
to his proof.

01:09:13.410 --> 01:09:15.770
So that's the bug and the fix.

01:09:15.770 --> 01:09:18.430
Let me tell you some
generalizations,

01:09:18.430 --> 01:09:20.210
