01:09:37.990 --> 01:09:57.750
theorem, which is that if you
have any continuous function,

01:09:57.750 --> 01:10:04.090
I should say let's
think of it as a curve,

01:10:04.090 --> 01:10:10.150
has an epsilon approximation
as a polynomial.

01:10:15.950 --> 01:10:17.530
OK, so in particular
what this tells

01:10:17.530 --> 01:10:19.790
us is if we have some
crazy curve we want

01:10:19.790 --> 01:10:24.830
to make, like signature,
then you can approximate it

01:10:24.830 --> 01:10:29.670
by a polynomial of the form that
we analyzed, this [INAUDIBLE]

01:10:29.670 --> 01:10:34.240
of x y equals 0.

01:10:34.240 --> 01:10:36.340
And the polynomial will
actually look like this,

01:10:36.340 --> 01:10:38.040
It's a little bit
ugly, if you've ever

01:10:38.040 --> 01:10:39.980
seen these constructions.

01:10:39.980 --> 01:10:44.930
But it will be always within
an epsilon thickness of Eric,

01:10:44.930 --> 01:10:48.770
always Eric, never
any other curve.

01:10:48.770 --> 01:10:51.310
All right so you can apply
this to make your signature

01:10:51.310 --> 01:10:53.962
or make whatever crazy
curve you have in mind.

01:10:53.962 --> 01:10:54.795
That's kind of nice.

01:10:57.320 --> 01:10:59.765
So this is why you can sign
your name using polynomials.

01:11:02.390 --> 01:11:03.899
So that's an easy application.

01:11:03.899 --> 01:11:04.773
Some generalizations.

01:11:13.276 --> 01:11:14.260
All right.

01:11:14.260 --> 01:11:20.340
You can do curves
in d dimensions.

01:11:20.340 --> 01:11:22.520
We talked about two dimensions.

01:11:22.520 --> 01:11:24.130
You can generalize that.

01:11:24.130 --> 01:11:28.530
You can also do surfaces
in d dimensions.

01:11:28.530 --> 01:11:31.440
Basically if you want to specify
a curve in three dimensions,

01:11:31.440 --> 01:11:35.820
you need two equations
to constrain it down

01:11:35.820 --> 01:11:37.449
to a one dimensional thing.

01:11:37.449 --> 01:11:38.990
Generally you start
with d dimensions

01:11:38.990 --> 01:11:41.156
and you can remove however
many dimensions you want.

01:11:41.156 --> 01:11:42.710
You'll get some
subsurface in there.

01:11:42.710 --> 01:11:44.860
Just add a bunch of
polynomial constraints.

01:11:44.860 --> 01:11:47.350
You can do that.

01:11:47.350 --> 01:11:49.520
Other fun facts.

01:11:49.520 --> 01:11:54.852
The number of edges you
need is about n to the d.

01:11:54.852 --> 01:11:58.960
This is being careful
about reusing structure.

01:11:58.960 --> 01:12:01.950
In the plane you can deal
with n squared edges.

01:12:01.950 --> 01:12:03.050
And that's optimal.

01:12:03.050 --> 01:12:04.800
You can show you
need n squared edges

01:12:04.800 --> 01:12:09.390
to construct certain
polynomials in the plane.

01:12:09.390 --> 01:12:13.560
In three dimensions you're
going to need more, turns out.

01:12:13.560 --> 01:12:15.540
Basically, because the
constructions we used

01:12:15.540 --> 01:12:18.420
want to work in a plane, and
if you live in d dimensions,

01:12:18.420 --> 01:12:20.040
you have to add lots
of edges to force

01:12:20.040 --> 01:12:23.370
it to live in two dimensions.

01:12:23.370 --> 01:12:28.010
So you can do the computation,
add the numbers, and so on.

01:12:28.010 --> 01:12:30.398
What other good things?

01:12:30.398 --> 01:12:33.110
All right, for the
mathematicians,

01:12:33.110 --> 01:12:39.450
you can make any compact
semi algebraic set.

01:12:44.020 --> 01:12:46.900
It's basically a
fancy way to say

01:12:46.900 --> 01:12:48.435
you can add polynomial
constraints,

01:12:48.435 --> 01:12:51.610
but you can also take
unions of solution sets.

01:12:51.610 --> 01:12:53.530
So I could take the
union of five curves

01:12:53.530 --> 01:12:57.525
that I like, or I can take the
intersection of five curves

01:12:57.525 --> 01:12:59.030
that I like.

01:12:59.030 --> 01:13:00.990
Bunch of things
you can do, that's

01:13:00.990 --> 01:13:03.010
the meaning of semi
algebraic set, polynomials

01:13:03.010 --> 01:13:04.135
and union and intersection.

01:13:08.090 --> 01:13:12.800
These are all proved in paper
with Tim Avit and Reid Barton

01:13:12.800 --> 01:13:15.230
from this class six years ago.

01:13:15.230 --> 01:13:19.710
Another fun fact
from that paper is

01:13:19.710 --> 01:13:23.440
that it's coNP-hard
to test rigidity.

01:13:26.690 --> 01:13:30.930
Rigidity is the
topic of next class.

01:13:30.930 --> 01:13:33.460
You're given a linkage,
does it move it all?

01:13:33.460 --> 01:13:34.950
And you can use
these constructions

01:13:34.950 --> 01:13:38.160
to mean, to show that something
will move at all if and only

01:13:38.160 --> 01:13:40.440
if all these polynomials
have a solution.

01:13:40.440 --> 01:13:43.520
And that turns out
to be really hard.

01:13:43.520 --> 01:13:46.110
And it's something
called coNP-hard,

01:13:46.110 --> 01:13:48.110
which is almost the
same as NP-hard.

01:13:48.110 --> 01:13:51.170
it's just for rigidity,
it's really easy

01:13:51.170 --> 01:13:53.530
to prove that something is
not rigid, you just move it.

01:13:53.530 --> 01:13:56.020
It's a little harder to show
that it can't move in any way.

01:13:56.020 --> 01:13:59.060
So that's for those who know
coNP, it's coNP, not NP.

01:14:01.820 --> 01:14:02.570
Cool.

01:14:02.570 --> 01:14:05.550
Those are various
generalizations.

01:14:05.550 --> 01:14:09.290
Big open problem
here is what if you

01:14:09.290 --> 01:14:11.639
forbid the edges from crossing.

01:14:11.639 --> 01:14:13.180
This actually came
up in lecture one.

01:14:13.180 --> 01:14:13.950
Someone asked it.

01:14:13.950 --> 01:14:19.186
It was first posed that I know
from Don Shimamoto in 2004,

01:14:19.186 --> 01:14:20.980
I was giving a talk.

01:14:20.980 --> 01:14:22.880
And all these
constructions, especially

01:14:22.880 --> 01:14:25.110
the contra-parallelogram,
need to have

01:14:25.110 --> 01:14:27.247
edges that cross each other.

01:14:27.247 --> 01:14:28.830
Next class will also
be about the case

01:14:28.830 --> 01:14:30.210
where edges cross
each other but soon

01:14:30.210 --> 01:14:31.506
we are going to
enter the case where

01:14:31.506 --> 01:14:32.797
edges are not allowed to cross.

01:14:32.797 --> 01:14:34.650
Can you do any of
this stuff, construct

01:14:34.650 --> 01:14:36.500
any interesting polynomials?

01:14:36.500 --> 01:14:38.820
Even constructing a straight
line, I think is open.

01:14:38.820 --> 01:14:41.750
The peaucellier linkage
definitely doesn't work.

01:14:41.750 --> 01:14:43.250
Maybe there are
some other linkages,

01:14:43.250 --> 01:14:44.570
we'd have to check them.

01:14:44.570 --> 01:14:47.190
But definitely Kempe's
universality result

01:14:47.190 --> 01:14:51.040
is open for non-crossing edges.

01:14:51.040 --> 01:14:52.814
I have some fun
projects like it'd

01:14:52.814 --> 01:14:54.230
be fun to implement
this algorithm

01:14:54.230 --> 01:14:56.277
and see this thing run.

01:14:56.277 --> 01:14:58.360
You could build a sculpture
out of Kempe linkages.

01:14:58.360 --> 01:15:00.170
They're a little
bit tedious I would

01:15:00.170 --> 01:15:02.810
say to make interesting curves,
but there's some cool ones.

01:15:02.810 --> 01:15:07.310
Like in the notes I have a
link to the letter C made out

01:15:07.310 --> 01:15:08.300
of a linkage.

01:15:08.300 --> 01:15:10.860
You could do a whole
alphabet, be kind of fun.

01:15:10.860 --> 01:15:12.810
Have these things cranking
around and spelling

01:15:12.810 --> 01:15:18.060
all sorts of, actually spelling
names would be the idea.

01:15:18.060 --> 01:15:21.760
Another fun application that I
thought I would just throw in.

01:15:21.760 --> 01:15:24.740
If you are, back to origami.

01:15:24.740 --> 01:15:27.660
Origami can in some
sense simulate linkages.

01:15:27.660 --> 01:15:29.431
And the motivation for
this is you've, you

01:15:29.431 --> 01:15:31.930
know you've designed, you just
design all these awesome tree

01:15:31.930 --> 01:15:35.500
maker diagrams for
your problem set.

01:15:35.500 --> 01:15:37.660
And you realize, oh
man, there's points

01:15:37.660 --> 01:15:39.730
all over the place on
this piece of paper.

01:15:39.730 --> 01:15:41.711
How the heck am I
going to find, if I

01:15:41.711 --> 01:15:43.460
had to make origami
diagrams, first I say,

01:15:43.460 --> 01:15:45.800
oh you do this step, then
this step, then this step.

01:15:45.800 --> 01:15:50.490
How am I going to tell someone
oh, just fold to root 3 over

01:15:50.490 --> 01:15:54.780
7 comma root 5
plus root 7 over 4,

01:15:54.780 --> 01:15:56.510
Which you could figure
out in some sense

01:15:56.510 --> 01:15:59.420
from those geometries what
all those coordinates are.

01:15:59.420 --> 01:16:03.210
How do you tell
someone to fold there?

01:16:03.210 --> 01:16:06.540
Well, you could
use a polynomial.

01:16:06.540 --> 01:16:10.350
Could say oh, you've
got to construct root 5.

01:16:10.350 --> 01:16:11.540
Or what's a tough one?

01:16:14.620 --> 01:16:20.440
Let's say you want to compute
the fifth root of 103.

01:16:20.440 --> 01:16:21.420
Is that prime?

01:16:21.420 --> 01:16:23.250
I think so.

01:16:23.250 --> 01:16:25.660
So some nasty thing like this.

01:16:25.660 --> 01:16:28.510
You say oh well, I
would really like

01:16:28.510 --> 01:16:31.890
x to the fifth to equal 103.

01:16:31.890 --> 01:16:34.330
If I could solve
this polynomial,

01:16:34.330 --> 01:16:36.509
then I could
construct this number.

01:16:36.509 --> 01:16:37.800
How do I solve that polynomial?

01:16:37.800 --> 01:16:40.860
Well I'm all about solving
polynomials using linkages.

01:16:40.860 --> 01:16:43.580
I could build a crazy
linkage device out

01:16:43.580 --> 01:16:45.050
of my piece of paper.

01:16:45.050 --> 01:16:47.030
Don't try this at home, please.

01:16:47.030 --> 01:16:51.120
But in theory, you could come up
with these n really long bars,

01:16:51.120 --> 01:16:54.260
fold them around, and
think of them as linkages.

01:16:54.260 --> 01:16:58.740
And you tell people, oh well you
just need to align these dots,

01:16:58.740 --> 01:17:02.990
you may make little pinches on
at the ends of these things,

01:17:02.990 --> 01:17:05.330
those simulate the
edges of your linkage.

01:17:05.330 --> 01:17:08.350
And then you just tell people
to move these creases around

01:17:08.350 --> 01:17:11.640
until this point
lies on some line.

01:17:11.640 --> 01:17:14.250
And then you've solved
your polynomial.

01:17:14.250 --> 01:17:16.140
And this is a natural
generalization

01:17:16.140 --> 01:17:18.790
in some sense to something
called origami axioms, which

01:17:18.790 --> 01:17:20.770
we will probably talk
about at some point.

01:17:20.770 --> 01:17:22.850
Usually you think about
doing one fold at a time.

01:17:22.850 --> 01:17:24.985
You want to make one fold
so that this point maps

01:17:24.985 --> 01:17:27.110
onto this line, and this
point maps onto this line.

01:17:27.110 --> 01:17:29.110
That's the typical
origami axiom.

01:17:29.110 --> 01:17:29.850
It's pretty good.

01:17:29.850 --> 01:17:31.980
It can trisect angles
and it can do fun things.

01:17:31.980 --> 01:17:34.692
But it can really only
solve degree four equations.

01:17:34.692 --> 01:17:36.400
You want to solve a
degree five equation,

01:17:36.400 --> 01:17:38.550
you need some higher
level techniques.

01:17:38.550 --> 01:17:40.840
And one way to do that is
with Kempe's universality.

01:17:40.840 --> 01:17:44.910
It's pretty impractical,
but at least in theory you

01:17:44.910 --> 01:17:48.850
can do anything, you can
locate any point you want,

01:17:48.850 --> 01:17:50.820
any algebraic point,
which are the things you'd

01:17:50.820 --> 01:17:57.192
want from tree maker, using
this technique, little crazy.

01:17:57.192 --> 01:17:58.650
There are other
ways to do it, too.

01:17:58.650 --> 01:18:01.685
But this one way to do it,
as mentioned in the textbook.

01:18:01.685 --> 01:18:02.185
Questions.

01:18:05.760 --> 01:18:06.642
All right.

01:18:06.642 --> 01:18:07.850
That's how to sign your name.

01:18:07.850 --> 01:18:11.670
Next time we'll talk about
rigidity and other fun linkage

01:18:11.670 --> 01:18:13.220
problems.

